05606 /**
05607  * cvmx_gmx#_bad_reg
05608  *
05609  * GMX_BAD_REG = A collection of things that have gone very, very wrong
05610  *
05611  *
05612  * Notes:
05613  * In XAUI mode, only the lsb (corresponding to port0) of INB_NXA, LOSTSTAT, OUT_OVR, are used.
05614  *
05615  */
05616 union cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg {
05617     uint64_t u64;
05618     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_s {
05619 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05620     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05621     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;  /**< Inbound port > GMX_RX_PRTS */
05622     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;  /**< TX Statistics overflow
05623                                                          The common FIFO to SGMII and XAUI had an overflow
05624                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
05625     uint64_t loststat                     : 4;  /**< TX Statistics data was over-written
05626                                                          In SGMII, one bit per port
05627                                                          In XAUI, only port0 is used
05628                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
05629     uint64_t reserved_18_21               : 4;
05630     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 16; /**< Outbound data FIFO overflow (per port) */
05631     uint64_t ncb_ovr                      : 1;  /**< Outbound NCB FIFO Overflow */
05632     uint64_t out_col                      : 1;  /**< Outbound collision occured between PKO and NCB */
05633 #else
05634     uint64_t out_col                      : 1;
05635     uint64_t ncb_ovr                      : 1;
05636     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 16;
05637     uint64_t reserved_18_21               : 4;
05638     uint64_t loststat                     : 4;
05639     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;
05640     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;
05641     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05642 #endif
05643     } s;
05644     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn30xx {
05645 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05646     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05647     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;  /**< Inbound port > GMX_RX_PRTS */
05648     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;  /**< TX Statistics overflow */
05649     uint64_t reserved_25_25               : 1;
05650     uint64_t loststat                     : 3;  /**< TX Statistics data was over-written (per RGM port)
05651                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
05652     uint64_t reserved_5_21                : 17;
05653     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 3;  /**< Outbound data FIFO overflow (per port) */
05654     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
05655 #else
05656     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
05657     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 3;
05658     uint64_t reserved_5_21                : 17;
05659     uint64_t loststat                     : 3;
05660     uint64_t reserved_25_25               : 1;
05661     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;
05662     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;
05663     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05664 #endif
05665     } cn30xx;
05666     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn30xx       cn31xx;
05667     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_s            cn38xx;
05668     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_s            cn38xxp2;
05669     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn30xx       cn50xx;
05670     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx {
05671 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05672     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05673     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;  /**< Inbound port > GMX_RX_PRTS */
05674     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;  /**< TX Statistics overflow
05675                                                          The common FIFO to SGMII and XAUI had an overflow
05676                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
05677     uint64_t loststat                     : 4;  /**< TX Statistics data was over-written
05678                                                          In SGMII, one bit per port
05679                                                          In XAUI, only port0 is used
05680                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
05681     uint64_t reserved_6_21                : 16;
05682     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 4;  /**< Outbound data FIFO overflow (per port) */
05683     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
05684 #else
05685     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
05686     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 4;
05687     uint64_t reserved_6_21                : 16;
05688     uint64_t loststat                     : 4;
05689     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;
05690     uint64_t inb_nxa                      : 4;
05691     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05692 #endif
05693     } cn52xx;
05694     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn52xxp1;
05695     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn56xx;
05696     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn56xxp1;
05697     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_s            cn58xx;
05698     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_s            cn58xxp1;
05699     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn61xx;
05700     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn63xx;
05701     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn63xxp1;
05702     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn66xx;
05703     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn68xx;
05704     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn68xxp1;
05705     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn70xx;
05706     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cn70xxp1;
05707     struct cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_cn52xx       cnf71xx;
05708 };
05709 typedef union cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg cvmx_gmxx_bad_reg_t;

05711 /**
05712  * cvmx_gmx#_bist
05713  *
05714  * GMX_BIST = GMX BIST Results
05715  *
05716  */
05717 union cvmx_gmxx_bist {

05856 /**
05857  * cvmx_gmx#_bpid_map#
05858  *
05859  * Notes:
05860  * GMX will build BPID_VECTOR<15:0> using the 16 GMX_BPID_MAP entries and the BPID
05861  * state from IPD.  In XAUI/RXAUI mode when PFC/CBFC/HiGig2 is used, the
05862  * BPID_VECTOR becomes the logical backpressure.  In XAUI/RXAUI mode when
05863  * PFC/CBFC/HiGig2 is not used or when in 4xSGMII mode, the BPID_VECTOR can be used
05864  * with the GMX_BPID_MSK register to determine the physical backpressure.
05865  *
05866  * In XAUI/RXAUI mode, the entire BPID_VECTOR<15:0> is available determining physical
05867  * backpressure for the single XAUI/RXAUI interface.
05868  *
05869  * In SGMII mode, BPID_VECTOR is broken up as follows:
05870  *    SGMII interface0 uses BPID_VECTOR<3:0>
05871  *    SGMII interface1 uses BPID_VECTOR<7:4>
05872  *    SGMII interface2 uses BPID_VECTOR<11:8>
05873  *    SGMII interface3 uses BPID_VECTOR<15:12>
05874  *
05875  * In all SGMII configurations, and in some XAUI/RXAUI configurations, the
05876  * interface protocols only support physical backpressure. In these cases, a single
05877  * BPID will commonly drive the physical backpressure for the physical
05878  * interface. We provide example programmings for these simple cases.
05879  *
05880  * In XAUI/RXAUI mode where PFC/CBFC/HiGig2 is not used, an example programming
05881  * would be as follows:
05882  *
05883  *    @verbatim
05884  *    GMX_BPID_MAP0[VAL]    = 1;
05885  *    GMX_BPID_MAP0[BPID]   = xaui_bpid;
05886  *    GMX_BPID_MSK[MSK_OR]  = 1;
05887  *    GMX_BPID_MSK[MSK_AND] = 0;
05888  *    @endverbatim
05889  *
05890  * In SGMII mode, an example programming would be as follows:
05891  *
05892  *    @verbatim
05893  *    for (i=0; i<4; i++) [
05894  *       if (GMX_PRTi_CFG[EN]) [
05895  *          GMX_BPID_MAP(i*4)[VAL]    = 1;
05896  *          GMX_BPID_MAP(i*4)[BPID]   = sgmii_bpid(i);
05897  *          GMX_BPID_MSK[MSK_OR]      = (1 << (i*4)) | GMX_BPID_MSK[MSK_OR];
05898  *       ]
05899  *    ]
05900  *    GMX_BPID_MSK[MSK_AND] = 0;
05901  *    @endverbatim
05902  */
05903 union cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx {
05904     uint64_t u64;
05905     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx_s {
05906 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05907     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
05908     uint64_t status                       : 1;  /**< Current received BP from IPD */
05909     uint64_t reserved_9_15                : 7;
05910     uint64_t val                          : 1;  /**< Table entry is valid */
05911     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
05912     uint64_t bpid                         : 6;  /**< Backpressure ID the entry maps to */
05913 #else
05914     uint64_t bpid                         : 6;
05915     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
05916     uint64_t val                          : 1;
05917     uint64_t reserved_9_15                : 7;
05918     uint64_t status                       : 1;
05919     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
05920 #endif
05921     } s;
05922     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx_s          cn68xx;
05923     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx_s          cn68xxp1;
05924 };
05925 typedef union cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx cvmx_gmxx_bpid_mapx_t;
05926 
05927 /**
05928  * cvmx_gmx#_bpid_msk
05929  */
05930 union cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk {
05931     uint64_t u64;
05932     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk_s {
05933 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05934     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
05935     uint64_t msk_or                       : 16; /**< Assert physical BP when the backpressure ID vector
05936                                                          combined with MSK_OR indicates BP as follows.
05937                                                          phys_bp_msk_or =
05938                                                           (BPID_VECTOR<x:y> & MSK_OR<x:y>) != 0
05939                                                          phys_bp = phys_bp_msk_or || phys_bp_msk_and
05940                                                          In XAUI/RXAUI mode, x=15, y=0
05941                                                          In SGMII mode, x/y are set depending on the SGMII
05942                                                          interface.
05943                                                          SGMII interface0, x=3,  y=0
05944                                                          SGMII interface1, x=7,  y=4
05945                                                          SGMII interface2, x=11, y=8
05946                                                          SGMII interface3, x=15, y=12 */
05947     uint64_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
05948     uint64_t msk_and                      : 16; /**< Assert physical BP when the backpressure ID vector
05949                                                          combined with MSK_AND indicates BP as follows.
05950                                                          phys_bp_msk_and =
05951                                                           (BPID_VECTOR<x:y> & MSK_AND<x:y>) == MSK_AND<x:y>
05952                                                          phys_bp = phys_bp_msk_or || phys_bp_msk_and
05953                                                          In XAUI/RXAUI mode, x=15, y=0
05954                                                          In SGMII mode, x/y are set depending on the SGMII
05955                                                          interface.
05956                                                          SGMII interface0, x=3,  y=0
05957                                                          SGMII interface1, x=7,  y=4
05958                                                          SGMII interface2, x=11, y=8
05959                                                          SGMII interface3, x=15, y=12 */
05960 #else
05961     uint64_t msk_and                      : 16;
05962     uint64_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
05963     uint64_t msk_or                       : 16;
05964     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
05965 #endif
05966     } s;
05967     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk_s           cn68xx;
05968     struct cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk_s           cn68xxp1;
05969 };
05970 typedef union cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk cvmx_gmxx_bpid_msk_t;

06050 /**
06051  * cvmx_gmx#_hg2_control
06052  *
06053  * Notes:
06054  * The HiGig2 TX and RX enable would normally be both set together for HiGig2 messaging. However
06055  * setting just the TX or RX bit will result in only the HG2 message transmit or the receive
06056  * capability.
06057  * PHYS_EN and LOGL_EN bits when 1, allow link pause or back pressure to PKO as per received
06058  * HiGig2 message. When 0, link pause and back pressure to PKO in response to received messages
06059  * are disabled.
06060  *
06061  * GMX*_TX_XAUI_CTL[HG_EN] must be set to one(to enable HiGig) whenever either HG2TX_EN or HG2RX_EN
06062  * are set.
06063  *
06064  * GMX*_RX0_UDD_SKP[LEN] must be set to 16 (to select HiGig2) whenever either HG2TX_EN or HG2RX_EN
06065  * are set.
06066  *
06067  * GMX*_TX_OVR_BP[EN<0>] must be set to one and GMX*_TX_OVR_BP[BP<0>] must be cleared to zero
06068  * (to forcibly disable HW-automatic 802.3 pause packet generation) with the HiGig2 Protocol when
06069  * GMX*_HG2_CONTROL[HG2TX_EN]=0. (The HiGig2 protocol is indicated by GMX*_TX_XAUI_CTL[HG_EN]=1
06070  * and GMX*_RX0_UDD_SKP[LEN]=16.) The HW can only auto-generate backpressure via HiGig2 messages
06071  * (optionally, when HG2TX_EN=1) with the HiGig2 protocol.
06072  */
06073 union cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control {
06074     uint64_t u64;
06075     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s {
06076 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06077     uint64_t reserved_19_63               : 45;
06078     uint64_t hg2tx_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable Transmission of HG2 phys and logl messages
06079                                                          When set, also disables HW auto-generated (802.3
06080                                                          and CBFC) pause frames. (OCTEON cannot generate
06081                                                          proper 802.3 or CBFC pause frames in HiGig2 mode.) */
06082     uint64_t hg2rx_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable extraction and processing of HG2 message
06083                                                          packet from RX flow. Physical logical pause info
06084                                                          is used to pause physical link, back pressure PKO
06085                                                          HG2RX_EN must be set when HiGig2 messages are
06086                                                          present in the receive stream. */
06087     uint64_t phys_en                      : 1;  /**< 1 bit physical link pause enable for recevied
06088                                                          HiGig2 physical pause message */
06089     uint64_t logl_en                      : 16; /**< 16 bit xof enables for recevied HiGig2 messages
06090                                                          or CBFC packets */
06091 #else
06092     uint64_t logl_en                      : 16;
06093     uint64_t phys_en                      : 1;
06094     uint64_t hg2rx_en                     : 1;
06095     uint64_t hg2tx_en                     : 1;
06096     uint64_t reserved_19_63               : 45;
06097 #endif
06098     } s;
06099     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn52xx;
06100     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn52xxp1;
06101     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn56xx;
06102     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn61xx;
06103     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn63xx;
06104     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn63xxp1;
06105     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn66xx;
06106     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn68xx;
06107     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn68xxp1;
06108     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn70xx;
06109     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cn70xxp1;
06110     struct cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_s        cnf71xx;
06111 };
06112 typedef union cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control cvmx_gmxx_hg2_control_t;

06114 /**
06115  * cvmx_gmx#_inf_mode
06116  *
06117  * GMX_INF_MODE = Interface Mode
06118  *
06119  */
06120 union cvmx_gmxx_inf_mode {
06121     uint64_t u64;
06122     struct cvmx_gmxx_inf_mode_s {
06123 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06124     uint64_t reserved_20_63               : 44;
06125     uint64_t rate                         : 4;  /**< SERDES speed rate
06126                                                          reset value is based on the QLM speed select
06127                                                          0 = 1.25  Gbaud
06128                                                          1 = 3.125 Gbaud
06129                                                          (only valid for GMX0 instance)
06130                                                          Software must not change RATE from its reset value */
06131     uint64_t reserved_12_15               : 4;
06132     uint64_t speed                        : 4;  /**< Interface Speed
06133                                                          QLM speed pins  which select reference clock
06134                                                          period and interface data rate.  If the QLM PLL
06135                                                          inputs are correct, the speed setting correspond
06136                                                          to the following data rates (in Gbaud).
06137                                                          0  = 5
06138                                                          1  = 2.5
06139                                                          2  = 2.5
06140                                                          3  = 1.25
06141                                                          4  = 1.25
06142                                                          5  = 6.25
06143                                                          6  = 5
06144                                                          7  = 2.5
06145                                                          8  = 3.125
06146                                                          9  = 2.5
06147                                                          10 = 1.25
06148                                                          11 = 5
06149                                                          12 = 6.25
06150                                                          13 = 3.75
06151                                                          14 = 3.125
06152                                                          15 = QLM disabled */
06153     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
06154     uint64_t mode                         : 3;  /**< Interface Electrical Operating Mode
06155                                                          - 0: SGMII (v1.8)
06156                                                          - 1: XAUI (IEEE 802.3-2005) */
06157     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
06158     uint64_t p0mii                        : 1;  /**< Port 0 Interface Mode
06159                                                          - 0: Port 0 is RGMII

06599 /**
06600  * cvmx_gmx#_prt#_cfg
06601  *
06602  * GMX_PRT_CFG = Port description
06603  *
06604  */
06605 union cvmx_gmxx_prtx_cfg {
06606     uint64_t u64;
06607     struct cvmx_gmxx_prtx_cfg_s {
06608 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06609     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
06610     uint64_t pknd                         : 6;  /**< Port Kind used for processing the packet by PKI */
06611     uint64_t reserved_14_15               : 2;
06612     uint64_t tx_idle                      : 1;  /**< TX Machine is idle */
06613     uint64_t rx_idle                      : 1;  /**< RX Machine is idle */
06614     uint64_t reserved_9_11                : 3;
06615     uint64_t speed_msb                    : 1;  /**< Link Speed MSB [SPEED_MSB:SPEED]
06616                                                          10 = 10Mbs operation
06617                                                          00 = 100Mbs operation
06618                                                          01 = 1000Mbs operation
06619                                                          11 = Reserved
06620                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
06621     uint64_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
06622     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;  /**< Slot Time for Half-Duplex operation
06623                                                          0 = 512 bitimes (10/100Mbs operation)
06624                                                          1 = 4096 bitimes (1000Mbs operation)
06625                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
06626     uint64_t duplex                       : 1;  /**< Duplex
06627                                                          0 = Half Duplex (collisions/extentions/bursts)
06628                                                          1 = Full Duplex
06629                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
06630     uint64_t speed                        : 1;  /**< Link Speed LSB [SPEED_MSB:SPEED]
06631                                                          10 = 10Mbs operation
06632                                                          00 = 100Mbs operation
06633                                                          01 = 1000Mbs operation
06634                                                          11 = Reserved
06635                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
06636     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< Link Enable
06637                                                          When EN is clear, packets will not be received
06638                                                          or transmitted (including PAUSE and JAM packets).
06639                                                          If EN is cleared while a packet is currently
06640                                                          being received or transmitted, the packet will
06641                                                          be allowed to complete before the bus is idled.
06642                                                          On the RX side, subsequent packets in a burst
06643                                                          will be ignored. */
06644 #else
06645     uint64_t en                           : 1;
06646     uint64_t speed                        : 1;
06647     uint64_t duplex                       : 1;
06648     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;
06649     uint64_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
06650     uint64_t speed_msb                    : 1;
06651     uint64_t reserved_9_11                : 3;
06652     uint64_t rx_idle                      : 1;
06653     uint64_t tx_idle                      : 1;
06654     uint64_t reserved_14_15               : 2;
06655     uint64_t pknd                         : 6;
06656     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
06657 #endif
06658     } s;
06659     struct cvmx_gmxx_prtx_cfg_cn30xx {
06660 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06661     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
06662     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;  /**< Slot Time for Half-Duplex operation
06663                                                          0 = 512 bitimes (10/100Mbs operation)
06664                                                          1 = 4096 bitimes (1000Mbs operation) */
06665     uint64_t duplex                       : 1;  /**< Duplex
06666                                                          0 = Half Duplex (collisions/extentions/bursts)
06667                                                          1 = Full Duplex */
06668     uint64_t speed                        : 1;  /**< Link Speed
06669                                                          0 = 10/100Mbs operation
06670                                                              (in RGMII mode, GMX_TX_CLK[CLK_CNT] >  1)
06671                                                              (in MII   mode, GMX_TX_CLK[CLK_CNT] == 1)
06672                                                          1 = 1000Mbs operation */
06673     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< Link Enable
06674                                                          When EN is clear, packets will not be received
06675                                                          or transmitted (including PAUSE and JAM packets).
06676                                                          If EN is cleared while a packet is currently
06677                                                          being received or transmitted, the packet will
06678                                                          be allowed to complete before the bus is idled.
06679                                                          On the RX side, subsequent packets in a burst
06680                                                          will be ignored. */
06681 #else
06682     uint64_t en                           : 1;
06683     uint64_t speed                        : 1;
06684     uint64_t duplex                       : 1;
06685     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;
06686     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
06687 #endif
06688     } cn30xx;

06700                                                          10 = 10Mbs operation
06701                                                          00 = 100Mbs operation
06702                                                          01 = 1000Mbs operation
06703                                                          11 = Reserved
06704                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */

06712                                                          1 = Full Duplex

06715                                                          10 = 10Mbs operation
06716                                                          00 = 100Mbs operation
06717                                                          01 = 1000Mbs operation
06718                                                          11 = Reserved
06719                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
06720     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< Link Enable
06721                                                          When EN is clear, packets will not be received
06722                                                          or transmitted (including PAUSE and JAM packets).
06723                                                          If EN is cleared while a packet is currently
06724                                                          being received or transmitted, the packet will
06725                                                          be allowed to complete before the bus is idled.
06726                                                          On the RX side, subsequent packets in a burst
06727                                                          will be ignored. */
06728 #else
06729     uint64_t en                           : 1;
06730     uint64_t speed                        : 1;

06732     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;
06733     uint64_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
06734     uint64_t speed_msb                    : 1;
06735     uint64_t reserved_9_11                : 3;
06736     uint64_t rx_idle                      : 1;
06737     uint64_t tx_idle                      : 1;
06738     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
06739 #endif
06740     } cn52xx;
06741     struct cvmx_gmxx_prtx_cfg_cn52xx      cn52xxp1;

07074 /**
07075  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_adr_cam_all_en
07076  *
07077  * GMX_RX_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN = Address Filtering Control Enable
07078  *
07079  */
07080 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_all_en {
07081     uint64_t u64;
07082     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_all_en_s {
07083 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07084     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07085     uint64_t en                           : 32; /**< CAM Entry Enables
07086 
07087                                                          GMX has 32 DMAC entries that can be accessed with
07088                                                          the GMX_RX[0..3]_ADR_CAM[0..5] CSRs.
07089                                                          These 32 DMAC entries can be used by any of the
07090                                                          four SGMII MACs or the XAUI MAC.
07091 
07092                                                          Each port interface has independent control of
07093                                                          which of the 32 DMAC entries to include in the
07094                                                          CAM lookup.
07095 
07096                                                          GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN was not present in legacy
07097                                                          GMX implemenations which had only eight DMAC CAM
07098                                                          entries. New applications may choose to ignore
07099                                                          GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_EN using GMX_RX_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN
07100                                                          instead.
07101 
07102                                                          EN represents the full 32 indepedent per MAC
07103                                                          enables.
07104 
07105                                                          Writes to EN will be reflected in
07106                                                          GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_EN[EN] and writes to
07107                                                          GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_EN[EN] will be reflected in EN.
07108                                                          Refer to GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_EN for the CSR mapping.
07109 
07110                                                          In XAUI mode, only GMX_RX0_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN is used
07111                                                          and GMX_RX[1,2,3]_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN should not be
07112                                                          used. */
07113 #else
07114     uint64_t en                           : 32;
07115     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07116 #endif
07117     } s;

07127 /**
07128  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_adr_cam_en
07129  *
07130  * GMX_RX_ADR_CAM_EN = Address Filtering Control Enable
07131  *
07132  */
07133 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en {
07134     uint64_t u64;
07135     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s {
07136 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07137     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
07138     uint64_t en                           : 8;  /**< CAM Entry Enables
07139 
07140                                                          GMX has 32 DMAC entries that can be accessed with
07141                                                          the GMX_RX[0..3]_ADR_CAM[0..5] CSRs.
07142                                                          These 32 DMAC entries can be used by any of the
07143                                                          four SGMII MACs or the XAUI MAC.
07144 
07145                                                          Each port interface has independent control of
07146                                                          which of the 32 DMAC entries to include in the
07147                                                          CAM lookup.
07148 
07149                                                          Legacy GMX implementations were able to CAM
07150                                                          against eight DMAC entries while current
07151                                                          implementations use 32 common entries.
07152                                                          This register is intended for legacy applications
07153                                                          that only require eight DMAC CAM entries per MAC.
07154                                                          New applications may choose to ignore
07155                                                          GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_EN using GMX_RXx_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN
07156                                                          instead.
07157 
07158                                                          EN controls the enables for the eight legacy CAM
07159                                                          entries as follows:
07160                                                           port0, EN = GMX_RX0_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN<7:0>]
07161                                                           port1, EN = GMX_RX1_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN<15:8>]
07162                                                           port2, EN = GMX_RX2_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN<23:16>]
07163                                                           port3, EN = GMX_RX3_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN<31:24>]
07164 
07165                                                          The full 32 indepedent per MAC enables are in
07166                                                          GMX_RX_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN.
07167 
07168                                                          Therefore, writes to GMX_RXX_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN]
07169                                                          will be reflected in EN and writes to EN will be
07170                                                          reflected in GMX_RXX_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN].
07171 
07172                                                          In XAUI mode, only GMX_RX0_ADR_CAM_EN is used and
07173                                                          GMX_RX[1,2,3]_ADR_CAM_EN should not be used. */
07174 #else
07175     uint64_t en                           : 8;
07176     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
07177 #endif
07178     } s;
07179     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s     cn30xx;
07180     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s     cn31xx;
07181     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s     cn38xx;
07182     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s     cn38xxp2;

07188     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_cam_en_s     cn58xx;

07202 /**
07203  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_adr_ctl
07204  *
07205  * GMX_RX_ADR_CTL = Address Filtering Control
07206  *
07207  *
07208  * Notes:
07209  * * ALGORITHM
07210  *   Here is some pseudo code that represents the address filter behavior.
07211  *
07212  *      @verbatim
07213  *      bool dmac_addr_filter(uint8 prt, uint48 dmac) [
07214  *        ASSERT(prt >= 0 && prt <= 3);
07215  *        if (is_bcst(dmac))                               // broadcast accept
07216  *          return (GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[BCST] ? ACCEPT : REJECT);
07217  *        if (is_mcst(dmac) & GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[MCST] == 1)   // multicast reject
07218  *          return REJECT;
07219  *        if (is_mcst(dmac) & GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[MCST] == 2)   // multicast accept
07220  *          return ACCEPT;
07221  *
07222  *        cam_hit = 0;
07223  *
07224  *        for (i=0; i<32; i++) [
07225  *          if (GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CAM_ALL_EN[EN<i>] == 0)
07226  *            continue;
07227  *          uint48 unswizzled_mac_adr = 0x0;
07228  *          for (j=5; j>=0; j--) [
07229  *             unswizzled_mac_adr = (unswizzled_mac_adr << 8) | GMX_RX[i>>3]_ADR_CAM[j][ADR<(i&7)*8+7:(i&7)*8>];
07230  *          ]
07231  *          if (unswizzled_mac_adr == dmac) [
07232  *            cam_hit = 1;
07233  *            break;
07234  *          ]
07235  *        ]
07236  *
07237  *        if (cam_hit)
07238  *          return (GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[CAM_MODE] ? ACCEPT : REJECT);
07239  *        else
07240  *          return (GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[CAM_MODE] ? REJECT : ACCEPT);
07241  *      ]
07242  *      @endverbatim
07243  *
07244  * * XAUI Mode
07245  *
07246  *   In XAUI mode, only GMX_RX0_ADR_CTL is used.  GMX_RX[1,2,3]_ADR_CTL should not be used.
07247  */
07248 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl {
07249     uint64_t u64;
07250     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s {
07251 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07252     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07253     uint64_t cam_mode                     : 1;  /**< Allow or deny DMAC address filter
07254                                                          0 = reject the packet on DMAC address match
07255                                                          1 = accept the packet on DMAC address match */
07256     uint64_t mcst                         : 2;  /**< Multicast Mode
07257                                                          0 = Use the Address Filter CAM
07258                                                          1 = Force reject all multicast packets
07259                                                          2 = Force accept all multicast packets
07260                                                          3 = Reserved */
07261     uint64_t bcst                         : 1;  /**< Accept All Broadcast Packets */
07262 #else
07263     uint64_t bcst                         : 1;
07264     uint64_t mcst                         : 2;
07265     uint64_t cam_mode                     : 1;
07266     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07267 #endif
07268     } s;
07269     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn30xx;
07270     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn31xx;
07271     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn38xx;
07272     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn38xxp2;
07273     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn50xx;
07274     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn52xx;
07275     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn52xxp1;
07276     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn56xx;
07277     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn56xxp1;
07278     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn58xx;
07279     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn58xxp1;
07280     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn61xx;
07281     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn63xx;
07282     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn63xxp1;
07283     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn66xx;
07284     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn68xx;
07285     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn68xxp1;
07286     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn70xx;
07287     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cn70xxp1;
07288     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_adr_ctl_s        cnf71xx;
07289 };

07292 /**
07293  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_decision
07294  *
07295  * GMX_RX_DECISION = The byte count to decide when to accept or filter a packet
07296  *
07297  *
07298  * Notes:
07299  * As each byte in a packet is received by GMX, the L2 byte count is compared
07300  * against the GMX_RX_DECISION[CNT].  The L2 byte count is the number of bytes
07301  * from the beginning of the L2 header (DMAC).  In normal operation, the L2
07302  * header begins after the PREAMBLE+SFD (GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK]=1) and any
07303  * optional UDD skip data (GMX_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN]).
07304  *
07305  * When GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is clear, PREAMBLE+SFD are prepended to the
07306  * packet and would require UDD skip length to account for them.
07307  *
07308  *                                                 L2 Size
07309  * Port Mode             <GMX_RX_DECISION bytes (default=24)       >=GMX_RX_DECISION bytes (default=24)
07310  *
07311  * Full Duplex           accept packet                             apply filters
07312  *                       no filtering is applied                   accept packet based on DMAC and PAUSE packet filters
07313  *
07314  * Half Duplex           drop packet                               apply filters
07315  *                       packet is unconditionally dropped         accept packet based on DMAC
07316  *
07317  * where l2_size = MAX(0, total_packet_size - GMX_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] - ((GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK]==1)*8)
07318  */
07319 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision {
07320     uint64_t u64;
07321     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s {
07322 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07323     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
07324     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;  /**< The byte count to decide when to accept or filter
07325                                                          a packet. */
07326 #else
07327     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;
07328     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
07329 #endif
07330     } s;
07331     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn30xx;
07332     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn31xx;
07333     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn38xx;
07334     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn38xxp2;
07335     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn50xx;
07336     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn52xx;
07337     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn52xxp1;
07338     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn56xx;
07339     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn56xxp1;
07340     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn58xx;
07341     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn58xxp1;
07342     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn61xx;
07343     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn63xx;
07344     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn63xxp1;
07345     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn66xx;
07346     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn68xx;
07347     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn68xxp1;
07348     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn70xx;
07349     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cn70xxp1;
07350     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_decision_s       cnf71xx;

07490 /**
07491  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_frm_ctl
07492  *
07493  * GMX_RX_FRM_CTL = Frame Control
07494  *
07495  *
07496  * Notes:
07497  * * PRE_STRP
07498  *   When PRE_CHK is set (indicating that the PREAMBLE will be sent), PRE_STRP
07499  *   determines if the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are thrown away or sent to the Octane
07500  *   core as part of the packet.
07501  *
07502  *   In either mode, the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are not counted toward the packet
07503  *   size when checking against the MIN and MAX bounds.  Furthermore, the bytes
07504  *   are skipped when locating the start of the L2 header for DMAC and Control
07505  *   frame recognition.
07506  *
07507  * * CTL_BCK/CTL_DRP
07508  *   These bits control how the HW handles incoming PAUSE packets.  Here are
07509  *   the most common modes of operation:
07510  *     CTL_BCK=1,CTL_DRP=1   - HW does it all
07511  *     CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=0   - SW sees all pause frames
07512  *     CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=1   - all pause frames are completely ignored
07513  *
07514  *   These control bits should be set to CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=0 in halfdup mode.
07515  *   Since PAUSE packets only apply to fulldup operation, any PAUSE packet
07516  *   would constitute an exception which should be handled by the processing
07517  *   cores.  PAUSE packets should not be forwarded.
07518  */
07519 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_frm_ctl {
07520     uint64_t u64;
07521     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_frm_ctl_s {
07522 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07523     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
07524     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;  /**< Timestamp mode
07525                                                          When PTP_MODE is set, a 64-bit timestamp will be
07526                                                          prepended to every incoming packet. The timestamp
07527                                                          bytes are added to the packet in such a way as to
07528                                                          not modify the packet's receive byte count.  This
07529                                                          implies that the GMX_RX_JABBER, MINERR,
07530                                                          GMX_RX_DECISION, GMX_RX_UDD_SKP, and the
07531                                                          GMX_RX_STATS_* do not require any adjustment as
07532                                                          they operate on the received packet size.
07533                                                          When the packet reaches PKI, its size will
07534                                                          reflect the additional bytes and is subject to
07535                                                          the restrictions below.
07536                                                          If PTP_MODE=1 and PRE_CHK=1, PRE_STRP must be 1.
07537                                                          If PTP_MODE=1,
07538                                                           PIP_PRT_CFGx[SKIP] should be increased by 8.
07539                                                           PIP_PRT_CFGx[HIGIG_EN] should be 0.
07540                                                           PIP_FRM_CHKx[MAXLEN] should be increased by 8.
07541                                                           PIP_FRM_CHKx[MINLEN] should be increased by 8.
07542                                                           PIP_TAG_INCx[EN] should be adjusted.
07543                                                           PIP_PRT_CFGBx[ALT_SKP_EN] should be 0. */
07544     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
07545     uint64_t null_dis                     : 1;  /**< When set, do not modify the MOD bits on NULL ticks
07546                                                          due to PARITAL packets */
07547     uint64_t pre_align                    : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE parser aligns the the SFD byte
07548                                                          regardless of the number of previous PREAMBLE
07549                                                          nibbles.  In this mode, PRE_STRP should be set to
07550                                                          account for the variable nature of the PREAMBLE.
07551                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
07552                                                          PREAMBLE features.
07553                                                          (SGMII at 10/100Mbs only) */
07554     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for non-min
07555                                                          sized pkts with padding in the client data
07556                                                          (PASS3 Only) */
07557     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for VLAN pkts */
07558     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE checking is  less strict.
07559                                                          GMX will begin the frame at the first SFD.
07560                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
07561                                                          PREAMBLE features.
07562                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
07563     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;  /**< Control Pause Frames can match station SMAC */
07564     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;  /**< Control Pause Frames can match globally assign
07565                                                          Multicast address */
07566     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;  /**< Forward pause information to TX block */
07567     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;  /**< Drop Control Pause Frames */
07568     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;  /**< Strip off the preamble (when present)
07569                                                          0=PREAMBLE+SFD is sent to core as part of frame
07570                                                          1=PREAMBLE+SFD is dropped
07571                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
07572                                                          PREAMBLE features.
07573                                                          If PTP_MODE=1 and PRE_CHK=1, PRE_STRP must be 1. */
07574     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;  /**< This port is configured to send a valid 802.3
07575                                                          PREAMBLE to begin every frame. GMX checks that a
07576                                                          valid PREAMBLE is received (based on PRE_FREE).
07577                                                          When a problem does occur within the PREAMBLE
07578                                                          seqeunce, the frame is marked as bad and not sent
07579                                                          into the core.  The GMX_GMX_RX_INT_REG[PCTERR]
07580                                                          interrupt is also raised.
07581                                                          When GMX_TX_XAUI_CTL[HG_EN] is set, PRE_CHK
07582                                                          must be zero.
07583                                                          If PTP_MODE=1 and PRE_CHK=1, PRE_STRP must be 1. */
07584 #else
07585     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;
07586     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;
07587     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;
07588     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;
07589     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;
07590     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;
07591     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;
07592     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;
07593     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;
07594     uint64_t pre_align                    : 1;
07595     uint64_t null_dis                     : 1;
07596     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
07597     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;
07598     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
07599 #endif
07600     } s;
07601     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_frm_ctl_cn30xx {
07602 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07603     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
07604     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for non-min
07605                                                          sized pkts with padding in the client data */
07606     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for VLAN pkts */
07607     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;  /**< Allows for less strict PREAMBLE checking.
07608                                                          0-7 cycles of PREAMBLE followed by SFD (pass 1.0)
07609                                                          0-254 cycles of PREAMBLE followed by SFD (else) */

07885 
07886 /**
07887  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_frm_max
07888  *
07889  * GMX_RX_FRM_MAX = Frame Max length
07890  *
07891  *
07892  * Notes:
07893  * In spi4 mode, all spi4 ports use prt0 for checking.
07894  *
07895  * When changing the LEN field, be sure that LEN does not exceed
07896  * GMX_RX_JABBER[CNT]. Failure to meet this constraint will cause packets that
07897  * are within the maximum length parameter to be rejected because they exceed
07898  * the GMX_RX_JABBER[CNT] limit.
07899  */
07900 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_frm_max {

07902     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_frm_max_s {

07904     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
07905     uint64_t len                          : 16; /**< Byte count for Max-sized frame check
07906                                                          GMX_RXn_FRM_CHK[MAXERR] enables the check for
07907                                                          port n.
07908                                                          If enabled, failing packets set the MAXERR
07909                                                          interrupt and work-queue entry WORD2[opcode] is
07910                                                          set to OVER_FCS (0x3, if packet has bad FCS) or
07911                                                          OVER_ERR (0x4, if packet has good FCS).
07912                                                          LEN =< GMX_RX_JABBER[CNT] */
07913 #else
07914     uint64_t len                          : 16;
07915     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
07916 #endif
07917     } s;

08552 
08553 /**
08554  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_int_reg
08555  *
08556  * GMX_RX_INT_REG = Interrupt Register
08557  *
08558  *
08559  * Notes:
08560  * (1) exceptions will only be raised to the control processor if the
08561  *     corresponding bit in the GMX_RX_INT_EN register is set.
08562  *
08563  * (2) exception conditions 10:0 can also set the rcv/opcode in the received
08564  *     packet's workQ entry.  The GMX_RX_FRM_CHK register provides a bit mask
08565  *     for configuring which conditions set the error.
08566  *
08567  * (3) in half duplex operation, the expectation is that collisions will appear
08568  *     as either MINERR o r CAREXT errors.
08569  *
08570  * (4) JABBER - An RX Jabber error indicates that a packet was received which
08571  *              is longer than the maximum allowed packet as defined by the
08572  *              system.  GMX will truncate the packet at the JABBER count.
08573  *              Failure to do so could lead to system instabilty.
08574  *
08575  * (5) NIBERR - This error is illegal at 1000Mbs speeds
08576  *              (GMX_RX_PRT_CFG[SPEED]==0) and will never assert.
08577  *
08578  * (6) MAXERR - for untagged frames, the total frame DA+SA+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS >
08579  *              GMX_RX_FRM_MAX.  For tagged frames, DA+SA+VLAN+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS
08580  *              > GMX_RX_FRM_MAX + 4*VLAN_VAL + 4*VLAN_STACKED.
08581  *
08582  * (7) MINERR - total frame DA+SA+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS < 64
08583  *
08584  * (8) ALNERR - Indicates that the packet received was not an integer number of
08585  *              bytes.  If FCS checking is enabled, ALNERR will only assert if
08586  *              the FCS is bad.  If FCS checking is disabled, ALNERR will
08587  *              assert in all non-integer frame cases.
08588  *
08589  * (9) Collisions - Collisions can only occur in half-duplex mode.  A collision
08590  *                  is assumed by the receiver when the slottime
08591  *                  (GMX_PRT_CFG[SLOTTIME]) is not satisfied.  In 10/100 mode,
08592  *                  this will result in a frame < SLOTTIME.  In 1000 mode, it
08593  *                  could result either in frame < SLOTTIME or a carrier extend
08594  *                  error with the SLOTTIME.  These conditions are visible by...
08595  *
08596  *                  . transfer ended before slottime - COLDET
08597  *                  . carrier extend error           - CAREXT
08598  *
08599  * (A) LENERR - Length errors occur when the received packet does not match the
08600  *              length field.  LENERR is only checked for packets between 64
08601  *              and 1500 bytes.  For untagged frames, the length must exact
08602  *              match.  For tagged frames the length or length+4 must match.
08603  *
08604  * (B) PCTERR - checks that the frame begins with a valid PREAMBLE sequence.
08605  *              Does not check the number of PREAMBLE cycles.
08606  *
08607  * (C) OVRERR -
08608  *
08609  *              OVRERR is an architectural assertion check internal to GMX to
08610  *              make sure no assumption was violated.  In a correctly operating
08611  *              system, this interrupt can never fire.
08612  *
08613  *              GMX has an internal arbiter which selects which of 4 ports to
08614  *              buffer in the main RX FIFO.  If we normally buffer 8 bytes,
08615  *              then each port will typically push a tick every 8 cycles - if
08616  *              the packet interface is going as fast as possible.  If there
08617  *              are four ports, they push every two cycles.  So that's the
08618  *              assumption.  That the inbound module will always be able to
08619  *              consume the tick before another is produced.  If that doesn't
08620  *              happen - that's when OVRERR will assert.
08621  *
08622  * (D) In XAUI mode prt0 is used for interrupt logging.
08623  */
08624 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_int_reg {
08625     uint64_t u64;
08626     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_int_reg_s {
08627 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08628     uint64_t reserved_30_63               : 34;
08629     uint64_t wol                          : 1;  /**< A Wake-on-LAN event has occurred */
08630     uint64_t hg2cc                        : 1;  /**< HiGig2 received message CRC or Control char  error
08631                                                          Set when either CRC8 error detected or when
08632                                                          a Control Character is found in the message
08633                                                          bytes after the K.SOM
08634                                                          NOTE: HG2CC has higher priority than HG2FLD
08635                                                                i.e. a HiGig2 message that results in HG2CC
08636                                                                getting set, will never set HG2FLD. */
08637     uint64_t hg2fld                       : 1;  /**< HiGig2 received message field error, as below
08638                                                          1) MSG_TYPE field not 6'b00_0000
08639                                                             i.e. it is not a FLOW CONTROL message, which
08640                                                             is the only defined type for HiGig2
08641                                                          2) FWD_TYPE field not 2'b00 i.e. Link Level msg
08642                                                             which is the only defined type for HiGig2
08643                                                          3) FC_OBJECT field is neither 4'b0000 for
08644                                                             Physical Link nor 4'b0010 for Logical Link.
08645                                                             Those are the only two defined types in HiGig2 */
08646     uint64_t undat                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected Data
08647                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08648     uint64_t uneop                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected EOP
08649                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08650     uint64_t unsop                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected SOP
08651                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08652     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;  /**< Frame is terminated by control character other
08653                                                          than /T/.  The error propagation control
08654                                                          character /E/ will be included as part of the
08655                                                          frame and does not cause a frame termination.
08656                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08657     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;  /**< Reserved Sequence Deteted
08658                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08659     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;  /**< Remote Fault Sequence Deteted
08660                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08661     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;  /**< Local Fault Sequence Deteted
08662                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
08663     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;  /**< Pause packet was dropped due to full GMX RX FIFO */
08664     uint64_t phy_dupx                     : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkDuplex */
08665     uint64_t phy_spd                      : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkSpeed */
08666     uint64_t phy_link                     : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkStatus */
08667     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;  /**< Interframe Gap Violation
08668                                                          Does not necessarily indicate a failure
08669                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */

08672     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;  /**< False carrier error or extend error after slottime
08673                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
08674     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;  /**< Reserved opcodes */
08675     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;  /**< Bad Preamble / Protocol
08676                                                          In XAUI mode, the column of data that was bad
08677                                                          will be logged in GMX_RX_XAUI_BAD_COL */
08678     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;  /**< Internal Data Aggregation Overflow
08679                                                          This interrupt should never assert
08680                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
08681     uint64_t niberr                       : 1;  /**< Nibble error (hi_nibble != lo_nibble) */
08682     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;  /**< Skipper error */
08683     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with Data reception error */
08684     uint64_t lenerr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with length error */
08685     uint64_t alnerr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with an alignment error */
08686     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with FCS/CRC error */
08687     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with length > sys_length */
08688     uint64_t maxerr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with length > max_length */
08689     uint64_t carext                       : 1;  /**< Carrier extend error
08690                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
08691     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;  /**< Pause Frame was received with length<minFrameSize
08692                                                          Frame length checks are typically handled in PIP
08693                                                          (PIP_INT_REG[MINERR]), but pause frames are
08694                                                          normally discarded before being inspected by PIP. */
08695 #else
08696     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;
08697     uint64_t carext                       : 1;
08698     uint64_t maxerr                       : 1;
08699     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;
08700     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;
08701     uint64_t alnerr                       : 1;
08702     uint64_t lenerr                       : 1;
08703     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;
08704     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;
08705     uint64_t niberr                       : 1;
08706     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;
08707     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;
08708     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;
08709     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;
08710     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;
08711     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;
08712     uint64_t phy_link                     : 1;
08713     uint64_t phy_spd                      : 1;
08714     uint64_t phy_dupx                     : 1;
08715     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;
08716     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;
08717     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;
08718     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;
08719     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;
08720     uint64_t unsop                        : 1;
08721     uint64_t uneop                        : 1;
08722     uint64_t undat                        : 1;

08727 #endif
08728     } s;
08729     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_int_reg_cn30xx {
08730 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08731     uint64_t reserved_19_63               : 45;
08732     uint64_t phy_dupx                     : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkDuplex */
08733     uint64_t phy_spd                      : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkSpeed */
08734     uint64_t phy_link                     : 1;  /**< Change in the RMGII inbound LinkStatus */
08735     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;  /**< Interframe Gap Violation
08736                                                          Does not necessarily indicate a failure */
08737     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;  /**< Collision Detection */
08738     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;  /**< False carrier error or extend error after slottime */
08739     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;  /**< RGMII reserved opcodes */
08740     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;  /**< Bad Preamble / Protocol */
08741     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;  /**< Internal Data Aggregation Overflow
08742                                                          This interrupt should never assert */

09163                                                          3) FC_OBJECT field is neither 4'b0000 for
09164                                                          Physical Link nor 4'b0010 for Logical Link.
09165                                                          Those are the only two defined types in HiGig2 */
09166     uint64_t undat                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected Data
09167                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09168     uint64_t uneop                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected EOP
09169                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09170     uint64_t unsop                        : 1;  /**< Unexpected SOP
09171                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09172     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;  /**< Frame is terminated by control character other
09173                                                          than /T/.  The error propagation control
09174                                                          character /E/ will be included as part of the
09175                                                          frame and does not cause a frame termination.
09176                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09177     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;  /**< Reserved Sequence Deteted
09178                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09179     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;  /**< Remote Fault Sequence Deteted
09180                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09181     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;  /**< Local Fault Sequence Deteted
09182                                                          (XAUI Mode only) */
09183     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;  /**< Pause packet was dropped due to full GMX RX FIFO */
09184     uint64_t reserved_16_18               : 3;
09185     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;  /**< Interframe Gap Violation
09186                                                          Does not necessarily indicate a failure
09187                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
09188     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;  /**< Collision Detection
09189                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X half-duplex only) */
09190     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;  /**< False carrier error or extend error after slottime
09191                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
09192     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;  /**< Reserved opcodes */
09193     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;  /**< Bad Preamble / Protocol
09194                                                          In XAUI mode, the column of data that was bad
09195                                                          will be logged in GMX_RX_XAUI_BAD_COL */
09196     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;  /**< Internal Data Aggregation Overflow
09197                                                          This interrupt should never assert
09198                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
09199     uint64_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
09200     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;  /**< Skipper error */
09201     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with Data reception error */
09202     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
09203     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with FCS/CRC error */
09204     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;  /**< Frame was received with length > sys_length */
09205     uint64_t reserved_2_2                 : 1;
09206     uint64_t carext                       : 1;  /**< Carrier extend error
09207                                                          (SGMII/1000Base-X only) */
09208     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;  /**< Pause Frame was received with length<minFrameSize
09209                                                          Frame length checks are typically handled in PIP
09210                                                          (PIP_INT_REG[MINERR]), but pause frames are
09211                                                          normally discarded before being inspected by PIP. */
09212 #else
09213     uint64_t minerr                       : 1;
09214     uint64_t carext                       : 1;
09215     uint64_t reserved_2_2                 : 1;
09216     uint64_t jabber                       : 1;
09217     uint64_t fcserr                       : 1;
09218     uint64_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
09219     uint64_t rcverr                       : 1;
09220     uint64_t skperr                       : 1;
09221     uint64_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
09222     uint64_t ovrerr                       : 1;
09223     uint64_t pcterr                       : 1;
09224     uint64_t rsverr                       : 1;
09225     uint64_t falerr                       : 1;
09226     uint64_t coldet                       : 1;
09227     uint64_t ifgerr                       : 1;
09228     uint64_t reserved_16_18               : 3;
09229     uint64_t pause_drp                    : 1;
09230     uint64_t loc_fault                    : 1;
09231     uint64_t rem_fault                    : 1;
09232     uint64_t bad_seq                      : 1;
09233     uint64_t bad_term                     : 1;
09234     uint64_t unsop                        : 1;
09235     uint64_t uneop                        : 1;
09236     uint64_t undat                        : 1;
09237     uint64_t hg2fld                       : 1;
09238     uint64_t hg2cc                        : 1;
09239     uint64_t wol                          : 1;
09240     uint64_t reserved_30_63               : 34;
09241 #endif
09242     } cn70xx;
09243     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_int_reg_cn70xx   cn70xxp1;
09244     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_int_reg_cn61xx   cnf71xx;

09248 /**
09249  * cvmx_gmx#_rx#_jabber
09250  *
09251  * GMX_RX_JABBER = The max size packet after which GMX will truncate
09252  *
09253  *
09254  * Notes:
09255  * CNT must be 8-byte aligned such that CNT[2:0] == 0
09256  *
09257  * The packet that will be sent to the packet input logic will have an
09258  * additionl 8 bytes if GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is set and
09259  * GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_STRP] is clear.  The max packet that will be sent is
09260  * defined as...
09261  *
09262  *      max_sized_packet = GMX_RX_JABBER[CNT]+((GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] & !GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_STRP])*8)
09263  *
09264  * In XAUI mode prt0 is used for checking.
09265  */
09266 union cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber {
09267     uint64_t u64;
09268     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s {
09269 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09270     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
09271     uint64_t cnt                          : 16; /**< Byte count for jabber check
09272                                                          Failing packets set the JABBER interrupt and are
09273                                                          optionally sent with opcode==JABBER
09274                                                          GMX will truncate the packet to CNT bytes */
09275 #else
09276     uint64_t cnt                          : 16;
09277     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
09278 #endif
09279     } s;
09280     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn30xx;
09281     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn31xx;
09282     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn38xx;
09283     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn38xxp2;
09284     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn50xx;
09285     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn52xx;
09286     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn52xxp1;
09287     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn56xx;
09288     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn56xxp1;
09289     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn58xx;
09290     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn58xxp1;
09291     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn61xx;
09292     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn63xx;
09293     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn63xxp1;
09294     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn66xx;
09295     struct cvmx_gmxx_rxx_jabber_s         cn68xx;
